What's a good name for this function?

```ts

const contactMeModalToggled = (shown: boolean, fromSection: string) => {
  if (!isAccepted) {
    if (shown) {
      logContactMeOpenEvent({ section: fromSection });
    } else {
      logContactMeDismissEvent();
    }
    setShowContactMeModal(true);
  } else {
    const { query } = router;
    logContinueToPostActivationPage();
    router.push({
      pathname: `/products/[id]/request-received`,
      query,
    });
  }
};
```

it's essentially the main CTA on the page - "Send me an offer". it will either take you to a form, or if you already filled it out, it will advance you to the next part of our sales journey.
Given its dual purpose of either showing the contact form or progressing the user forward, some potential names could be:

```typescript
const handlePrimaryCTA = (shown: boolean, fromSection: string) => { ... }
const handleLeadCapture = (shown: boolean, fromSection: string) => { ... }
const handleSalesProgress = (shown: boolean, fromSection: string) => { ... }
```

But I think the most accurate and descriptive name would be:

```typescript
const handleRequestOffer = (shown: boolean, fromSection: string) => { ... }
```

This name:
1. Clearly communicates the user's intent ("I want to request an offer")
2. Doesn't expose implementation details (whether it shows a modal or redirects)
3. Matches the business domain language ("offer" is a key concept in your system)
4. Is an action/verb which is good for handler naming

You might even want to split the logging from the core functionality:

```typescript
const handleRequestOffer = (fromSection: string) => {
  if (isAccepted) {
    logContinueToPostActivationPage();
    router.push({
      pathname: `/products/[id]/request-received`,
      query: router.query,
    });
  } else {
    logContactMeOpenEvent({ section: fromSection });
    setShowContactMeModal(true);
  }
};

const handleRequestOfferDismiss = () => {
  logContactMeDismissEvent();
  setShowContactMeModal(false);
};
```

This makes the intent even clearer and removes the somewhat awkward `shown` boolean parameter.
I agree with the latter naming and split. let's partially apply the first function so that we can increase the ergonomics a bit.
We can create a helper that pre-fills the `fromSection` parameter, making it more ergonomic to use in different components:

```typescript
const createRequestOfferHandler = (fromSection: string) => () => {
  handleRequestOffer(fromSection);
};

// Usage in components becomes really clean:
const FinancingSection = () => {
  const onRequestOffer = createRequestOfferHandler('Financing Section');
  return <Button onClick={onRequestOffer}>Request Offer</Button>;
};

const StickyHeader = () => {
  const onRequestOffer = createRequestOfferHandler('Sticky Header');
  return <Button onClick={onRequestOffer}>Request Offer</Button>;
};
```

Or if you prefer a more hooks-style approach:

```typescript
const useRequestOffer = (fromSection: string) => {
  return useCallback(() => handleRequestOffer(fromSection), [fromSection]);
};

// Usage:
const FinancingSection = () => {
  const onRequestOffer = useRequestOffer('Financing Section');
  return <Button onClick={onRequestOffer}>Request Offer</Button>;
};
```

Both approaches achieve the same goal of making the API more ergonomic by removing the need to specify the section every time the handler is called, but the hooks approach might fit better with your existing React patterns.
how can I specify a gridArea (name) with tailwind?

Tailwind CSS doesn't have built-in utilities for `grid-area` names. You'll need to either:

1. Use a custom class:
```tsx
// styles.css or your global CSS
.grid-area-sidebar {
  grid-area: sidebar;
}

// Component
<div className="grid-area-sidebar">
```

2. Use inline styles (not recommended but works):
```tsx
<div style={{ gridArea: 'sidebar' }}>
```

3. The recommended approach: Add a custom utility to your Tailwind config:
```js
// tailwind.config.js
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      gridArea: {
        'sidebar': 'sidebar',
        'main': 'main',
        'header': 'header',
        // ... other areas you need
      }
    }
  },
  plugins: [
    plugin(function({ addUtilities, theme }) {
      const gridAreas = theme('gridArea', {})
      const utilities = Object.entries(gridAreas).map(([key, value]) => ({
        [`.grid-area-${key}`]: {
          'grid-area': value
        }
      }))
      addUtilities(utilities)
    })
  ]
}
```

Then you can use it like:
```tsx
<div className="grid-area-sidebar">
```

Given that this is a common need, I'm a bit surprised Tailwind doesn't have this built in. If you need this in multiple places, I'd definitely go with option 3 as it keeps things consistent with the Tailwind utility-first approach.
I think it's easiest to use the style prop then.
Yes, for grid area names specifically, using the style prop is probably the most straightforward approach. It's one of those rare cases where the inline style is actually quite clean:

```tsx
<div
  className="grid [other-tailwind-classes]"
  style={{ gridArea: 'sidebar' }}
>
```

This is especially true if:
1. The grid areas are unique to specific layouts
2. You don't need to reuse them across many components
3. You want to keep the grid area names close to where you define the grid template areas

It's also easier to maintain than setting up custom Tailwind utilities for what might be a one-off naming need.
